

PRELIMINARY ALPHA SOFTWARE
DO NOT USE FOR PRODUCTION
DO NOT DISTRIBUTE


=============================================================================

loader is a object file execution engine, that does loading of ELF objects,
relocation and in-memory execution on basic block level. To do this, the
entire file is broken up into basic block code fragments and the possible
codeflow between the individual basic blocks is analyzed. Then this
information is removed from each basic block and the program is executed.

At the end of each basic block, the loader pops in and simulates the control
flow that would happen.

As for now, it only works on small programs and still has serious trouble
processing the GNU libc library. But object files linked with dietlibc
already work.


Input object files must be:

	- ELF relocateable object files
	- with symbol table information
	- without any .common symbols (STT_COMMON)
	- without any external references (i.e. completely self-contained)
	- without complicated manual control flow constructs (i.e. best works
	  vanilla GCC output)

How to create such an object is shown in the ldistfp/Makefile.

This release is just for you to toy around and maybe test with other small
programs.


Example usage:
--------------

# print list of possible arguments
./loader -h

# execute the program as usual "iob -h"
./loader -3 0 -q ldistfp/ldistfp-final-dietlibc.o main -- -h

# execute the program as usual "iob -u -n test.txt"
./loader -3 0 -q ldistfp/ldistfp-final-dietlibc.o main -- -u -n test.txt

# press enter to get to the next basic block
./loader ldistfp/ldistfp-final-dietlibc.o main -- -h

# skip the first 1000 basic blocks, then continue manually
./loader -Q -s 1000 ldistfp/ldistfp-final-dietlibc.o main -- -u -n test.txt

# generate and show a graph of the getenv function (you need to have
# the graphviz package and the "gv" postscript viewer installed)
./loader -v ldistfp/ldistfp-final-dietlibc.o getenv



